  "response": "Coups in Pakistan have been successful due to several key factors:\n\n1. Weak Democratic Institutions\n- Historically fragile parliamentary system\n- Frequent political instability\n- Lack of strong democratic traditions\n\n2. Military's Influential Role\n- Military has been powerful and politically well-organized\n- Strong internal cohesion and discipline\n- Perception of being more competent than civilian governments\n\n3. Socio-Political Conditions\n- Corruption in civilian governments\n- Economic challenges\n- Ethnic and regional tensions\n- Lack of effective governance\n\n4. Constitutional Vulnerabilities\n- Constitutional provisions that allowed military intervention\n- Weak checks and balances\n- Frequent political deadlocks\n\n5. International Context\n- Cold War dynamics\n- Strategic geopolitical importance\n- External support for military leadership\n\n6. Public Perception\n- Military often portrayed as a stabilizing force\n- Civilian leadership seen as ineffective\n- Some public support for military interventions\n\nThese factors combined made military coups relatively easier to execute in Pakistan, with successful takeovers occurring in 1958, 1969, 1977, and 1999. Each coup exploited existing political weaknesses and institutional fragilities.",
